f:[0, +\infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R} \text{ uniformly continuous at } [0, + \infty):
\forall \epsilon >0 \exists \delta >0 \text{ such that } \forall x,y \in [0, + \infty) \text{ with } |x-y|< \delta \Rightarrow |f(x)-f(y)|<\epsilon
f:[0, +\infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R} \text{ uniformly continuous at } [0, + \infty).
\text{Show that there are } a,b \geq 0 \text{ so that } |f(x)| \leq ax+b, \forall x \geq 0.
$$ $f:[0, +\infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R} \text{ uniformly continuous at } [0, + \infty):$ $\forall \epsilon >0 \exists \delta >0 \text{ such that } \forall x,y \in [0, + \infty) \text{ with } |x-y|< \delta \Rightarrow |f(x)-f(y)|<\epsilon$ 
\epsilon_0>0
\delta_0
x>0
f(x)
f(x)-f(x-\delta_0)+f(x-\delta_0)-f(x-2\delta_0)+f(x-2 \delta_0)-+ \dots -f(x-N \delta_0)+f(x-N \delta_0)-f(0)+f(0) 
N
x-N \delta_0
a=\epsilon_0/\delta_0
b=\epsilon_0+|f(0)|
N=\lfloor x/\delta_0 \rfloor \leq x/\delta_0.
\vert f(x) \rvert= \left| \left(\sum_{n=1}^{N} f(x-(n-1) \delta_0)-f(x-n \delta_0) \right)+f(x-N \delta_0)-f(0)+f(0) \right|  \leq \\ \sum_{n=1}^N \left|f(x-(n-1) \delta_0)-f(x-n \delta_0) \right|  +|f(x-N \delta_0)-f(0)|+|f(0)| \leq \\ N \epsilon_0+\epsilon_0+|f(0)| \leq \frac{\epsilon_0}{\delta_0} x+(\epsilon_0+|f(0)|). 
